page.text: The CSAH 22 (70th Street) roadway corridor, located between Goodview Avenue/Court and Hinton
Avenue in the northern part of Cottage Grove, Minnesota, is located in an area that consists of bluff
terrain and steep grades with substandard roadway vertical curves. Furthermore, the area has
experienced steady traffic growth that is expected to strain the existing roadway capacity. The area has
also been the location of severe crashes in the recent past, including a fatality and the area is viewed as
less than safe by the local community. However, the corridor overall does not rate any worse by crash
safety comparison to similar facilities. The crash rate for the corridor is 2.08 and the severity rate is
3.23. The Twin Cities metropolitan average for a similar facility is 3.0 with a severity rate of 4.2. In
response to expected area traffic growth and the desire to improve roadway performance and mobility
and address safety concern, the Washington County Public Works Department with the input of the City
of Cottage Grove have pursued a CSAH 22 (70th Street) Corridor Study to identify area improvement
features. The Study limits are 1000' west of Goodview Court/Avenue to approximately 1000' east of
Traffic turning movement counts were collected in January, 2010 and forecasted to project 2030 traffic
volumes using 20-year Mn/DOT State Aid growth rates historically associated with the region. Both
2010 and 2030 traffic volumes were used to model traffic operations for all analysis scenarios and to
define future roadway capacity needs. Crash history was compiled and the entire area was reviewed
for any other safety concerns. A focused roadway improvement layout plan was created to address
topography and roadway grade concerns. In addition, mobility features such as trails, sidewalks and a
previously studied pedestrian tunnel were incorporated into the analysis and layout.
Two scenarios were identified through the study process to compare against the existing layout. The
first, Build, analyzes a four-lane divided highway that would not only account for current corridor
concerns but also account for long term area growth. In the event that immediate funding is not
available, the study evaluates an additional layout with various incremental improvement measures
deemed Interim that can be applied to achieve some of the overall project goals for improvement with a
varying schedule. For each layout, preliminary costs were identified and the key features of each are
explained. The Build layout cost estimate is itemized by construction item as this layout is considered an
Applying the Build layout requires a large amount of excavation that may result in costly large retaining
walls and/or the need to purchase additional Right of Way. Interim measures may help achieve certain
project goals but may require design variances, additional roadway construction and may have a shorter
life span. As area traffic volumes increase, intersection traffic operations becomes strained and safety
concerns become exacerbated by decreased gaps and increased crash opportunity. The purpose of this
report is to analyze current and future traffic operations, investigate roadway safety improvements,
identify feasible area improvement measures now that can be implemented in the near and long terms ,
address possible Right of Way needs and generate preliminary improvement cost estimates.

page.text: CSAH 22 (70th Street) between Goodview Court/Avenue and Hinton Avenue is a two-lane minor arterial
roadway that runs through the northern part of Cottage Grove in Washington County, Minnesota.
Topography in this section of the City consists of bluff terrain and steep pitches with roadways that have
substandard vertical curves. This section of the County has experienced consistent growth that
traditionally has met traffic growth projections. The area has also experienced a history of severe
crashes. A recent fatal crash and an "A" type incapacitating injury crash at CSAH 22 and Hardwood
Avenue led to the restriping of the intersection in 2008 and the installation of a temporary signal system
later that year. The area carries safety concern from the surrounding community, however, the corridor
overall does not rate any worse by crash safety comparison to similar facilities. Wanting to address the
challenging terrain, potential roadway capacity issues and address safety concern has led the
Washington County Public Works Department to investigate future area improvements for this corridor.
The purpose of this report is to analyze current and future traffic operations, investigate roadway safety
improvements, identify feasible area improvement measures now that can be implemented in the near
and long terms , address possible Right of Way need and generate preliminary improvement cost
estimates. Project limits are 1000' west of Goodview Court/Avenue to approximately 1200' east of
Homestead Avenue/Ideal Avenue along CSAH 22. North and south limits depend on practical roadway
tie-in points. The project limits and corridor location are detailed on Figure 1. Project study
A site evaluation was undertaken to evaluate the current roadway layout, traffic control, speed limits
and other corridor features of CSAH 22 and each of the study intersections. Study intersections are
described below. Hinton Avenue north of CSAH 22 is also known as CSAH 13. Hinton and Hardwood
Avenues south of CSAH 22 are City of Cottage Grove Municipal State Aid routes.

calculations. Also, Washington County provided approach traffic counts completed in 2008 and 2009
which also resulted in small traffic volume discrepancies due to collection date differences. This data

The study area has experienced steady development in the recent past that has consistently met traffic
growth projections and is expected to see continued growth in the future. To project future traffic
volumes for this study, the Mn/DOT State Aid 20-year growth projection rate of 1.5 for Washington
County was utilized. This traffic growth factor is traditionally used to project future traffic volumes for a
roadway facility of this type and is based on historical traffic growth in the region. No additional large
traffic generating developments were considered for this report as none were immediately known by
the County and City . Therefore, no additional peak hour traffic was added beside the projected 1.5
background growth rate to account for continued growth outside the study corridor. For this study,
2030 is the proposed roadway improvement design year. As of report completion, no project
A four-lane divided roadway section is most capable of facilitating current and future area roadway need
to best serve Washington County and the City of Cottage Grove. This four-lane section was developed
by Stonebrooke from various meetings with both the City of Cottage Grove and Washington County staff
and is based on current Washington County, Mn/DOT State Aid, and AASHTO geometric design
standards for this type of roadway facility. The four-lane section is referred to in this report as the Build
layout. Components of the Build scenario are detailed below, with engineering reasoning for each. The
Build layout can be seen in Figures 3.1-3.7 which contains 2030 projected peak hour traffic turning
The Build layout is a four-lane divided highway with a 6' raised median and 10' shoulders. To comply
with Washington County access spacing guidelines, the intersections of CSAH 22 at Goodview Avenue
and Granada Avenue are proposed to be 3/4 access (See Figures 3.1-3.7). The hilly terrain and proximity
of homes provides the greatest design challenges for this layout. To avoid the need to acquire several
adjacent properties, large retaining walls would be needed to fit the roadway within existing Right of
Way. The Build layout contains items discussed at project management team meetings and a May 5,
2010 Cottage Grove City Council Workshop. Below is a description of key Build layout components.
1. Signalized traffic control at the intersection of CSAH 22 at Hinton Avenue: The intersection of CSAH
22 at Hinton Avenue is expected to be very close to meeting signal warrants by 2030. Projected 2030
intersection traffic volumes were applied with respect to traffic signal warrants defined in the 2005 MN
MUTCD. Traditionally Washington County prefers the following warrant parameters are met:
1. The intersection meets Warrant 1A, 1B (Eight Hour Vehicular Volume) or 7 (Crash Experience)
2. Current traffic volumes do not meet Warrant 1A or 1B, but development in the area may
occur such that the warrants will be met in a reasonable period of time.
Projected traffic levels are expected to meet Warrant 1A and be very close to meeting Warrant 1B.
2. 10' trail on north side of CSAH 22 and 6' sidewalk on the south side of CSAH 22: The in place trail
system along the north side of CSAH 22 will be improved by applying new pavement material and a
consistent 10' width to meet Washington County standards. A sidewalk along the south side of CSAH 22
will be added to increase pedestrian/bicycle mobility options.
3. 3/4 Access at the intersections of CSAH 22 at Goodview Avenue/Court and CSAH 22 at Granada
Avenue: Reducing access at these intersections helps improve safety and ensures consistency with
Washington County access spacing guidelines for the corridor. The raised directional medians
associated with these 3/4 intersections reduces the amount of traffic turning movements that can come
in conflict with each other and thus limits crash opportunities. Reducing conflict areas is especially
helpful at intersections with challenging sight lines. Vehicles intending to make left turns out of the side
streets will need to utilize available u-turns at adjacent intersections.
4. Right-in/right-out access to remain at Pine Arbor Lane: A right-in/right-out access is specified in the
current land use permit for this intersection. Access at this intersection is in accordance with
Washington County access spacing guidelines to provide more uniform traffic operation due to potential
queuing, sightline issues and proximity with the CSAH 22 at Hinton Avenue intersection.
5. Side street center medians: The direction from Washington County and the City of Cottage Grove is
to retain existing side street medians where possible and to maintain current neighborhood access
6. Vertical roadway profile improved: The vertical profile is proposed to be improved to meet State
Aid/AASHTO guidelines for 55 mph design speed. The only exception is at the intersection of CSAH 22 at
Hardwood Avenue. This vertical curve is set to meet 50 mph design speed (current posted speed) to
minimize a proposed large fill section. Improved grades help with sight distance and ease climbing and
descending, however, incorporating these improvements will result in large retaining walls. Without
retaining walls, tie-in points from the roadway to the surrounding topography would greatly impact
adjacent properties. Creating optimal sight lines that would allow for ease of side-street crossing
movements would require additional excavation of the hill between Goodview Avenue and Meadow

above, the proximity of area residences and large cut and fill areas required to achieve Mn/DOT and

Analysis was completed for both the existing and 20-year projected study timeframes of 2010 and 2030
in the AM and PM peak hours for the Existing and Build layouts. The intersection operation study was
based on the methodology of the 2000 Highway Capacity Manual through the use of SYNCHRO/Sim
Traffic operations analysis software programs for two-way stop, all-way stop and signalized
intersections. Results of the analysis are displayed as measures of effectiveness. Measures of
effectiveness display quantitative information about the performance of an intersection. The primary
measures that are used in the study are level of service, delay, and volume to capacity ratios. Because
SYNCHRO/Sim Traffic follows the Highway Capacity Manual methodology, total intersection delay and
level of service is defined for a signalized intersection whereas at unsignalized intersections, only
The operational analysis results are described as a level of service (LOS) ranging from A (best) to F
(worst). These letters serve to describe a range of operating conditions for different types of facilities.
Level of service is calculated based on the 2000 Highway Capacity Manual parameters, which is based on
control delay. Control delay is the wait time experienced by vehicles slowing down for a signal or stop
sign plus the time for a vehicle to speed up and traverse the intersection control into the traffic stream.
The average intersection control delay is the delay experienced by all motorists entering the intersection
averaged over all approaches to a signalized intersection. Level of service D is commonly used as an
acceptable design year LOS. The delay for unsignalized intersections is lower for each LOS compared to
signalized intersections due to the fact that drivers tend to accept longer delays at signals compared to
stop signs. Level of service and associated intersection delay for signalized and unsignalized
intersections is presented below in Table 2.
Volume to capacity ratio is the proportion of the actual traffic utilizing a facility to the facility's physical
ability to carry a specific maximum volume. This is calculated by dividing the total traffic using the
facility by the capacity of the facility. A ratio greater that 1.00 predicts that the facility will be unable to
discharge all the demand arriving on it. Such a situation would result in long queues and extensive
delays, or diversion to alternate routes.

Due to funding constraints, constructing a four-lane section may not be achievable in the near future.
Therefore, upon direction from Washington County and City of Cottage Grove staff, short-term
measures were prepared and analyzed that may achieve some of the overall goals for area improvement
by utilizing or improving existing facilities. The study area was analyzed from an engineering and
planning perspective to identify potential Interim improvements that may mitigate congestion issues
and enhance safety measures that can be implemented prior to full reconstruction funding being
available. Interim measures can be seen in Figures 5.1-5.7 and are described below with pros and cons
for each. All items maintain the climbing lane features already incorporated along CSAH 22. Traffic
operations closely mimic 2030 No-Build traffic operations as traffic control does not change, except at

text.b: 1. Restripe turn lanes with rebuilt/expanded shoulders along study corridor to provide exclusive left

page.text: turn lanes: Currently, the intersections of CSAH 22 at Goodview, Granada and Meadow Grass Avenues
have striping layouts consisting of thru-left and exclusive right lanes in the east and westbound
directions. Each intersection has experienced rear-end and sideswipe crashes that may be due to
interaction between vehicles waiting to turn left and thru traffic approaching from behind. These types
of crashes may be alleviated by revising the striping along CSAH 22 at the intersection to incorporate
mainline exclusive left turn lanes. Pros: Restriping lanes as stated above shifts traffic waiting for a left
turn out of the way of thru movement traffic and also utilizes the in-place paved roadway. Cons:
Shifting lanes would move the current thru lanes to the shoulder and remove right-turn lanes. A
historical review of in-place cross sections shows inconsistency of the pavement thickness between thru
lanes and shoulder sections. Consistent vehicle travel on inconsistent pavement thickness may lead to
pavement failure. In addition, thru travel lanes would be shifted to within recommended State Aid
design standards of 8' shoulders for this type of facility. In most instances, a 6' shoulder is feasible,
however, the condition of the in place shoulder and lane shift development may require either design
variances and/or rebuilding of shoulder sections.
2. Two-way left turn lane west of Goodview Avenue: Several driveways with direct access to CSAH 22
are located between the in-place raised median west of Goodview Avenue and the intersection. Shifting
the existing eastbound lanes 7' south and the existing westbound lane 7' north, a two-way left turn lane
can be established to service these driveways. Pros: Restriping lanes as stated above shifts traffic
waiting for a left turn out of the way of thru movement traffic and also utilizes the in-place paved
roadway. Cons: Shifting lanes would move the current thru lanes to the shoulder roadway section. A
historical review of in-place cross sections shows inconsistency of the pavement thickness between thru
lanes and shoulder sections. Consistent vehicle travel on inconsistent pavement thickness may lead to
pavement failure. In addition, thru travel lanes would be shifted to within recommended State Aid 8'
shoulder width areas and be located close to the north side pedestrian trail. There may also be concern
with a two-way left turn lane on a high speed facility.
3. Proactively purchase properties: The Build layout details several areas where large retaining walls
would be needed in order to tie into existing topography without impacting adjacent properties. In the
event these adjacent properties become available, the County/City can purchase these properties and
proactively prepare for future roadway expansion by increasing the existing CSAH 22 Right of Way.
Pros: Proposed retaining walls could be eliminated or minimized, reducing future costs and safety
concerns. Cons: The initial cost of this option is high and must be done with the understanding that the
expansion of CSAH 22 is almost certain.
4. Lengthened turn lanes at Hardwood Avenue along CSAH 22: The intersection of CSAH 22 at
Hardwood Avenue is located at the bottom of a sag vertical curve with greater than 8% grades on either
side. Due to these steep grades, safe stopping distance as defined in the Mn/DOT Road Design Manual
becomes longer. To best provide appropriate safe stopping distance required to safely utilize left turns
lanes, consideration should be given to extending the east and westbound left turn lanes. Pros: This
option provides additional length for east and westbound left turn lanes which may help reduce rear
end type crashes, especially in inclement conditions. Cons: This option reduces the length of truck
climbing lanes and moves the truck climbing lanes further uphill in both east and westbound directions.
5. Right turn lane into Goodview Court from CSAH 22: This area currently has a wide shoulder that
could be turned into an exclusive right turn lane. If a right turn lane is incorporated along with the
restriping of left turn lanes mentioned above, the additional right turn lane would need to be
constructed. Pros: Providing a turn lane moves right turning traffic out of the way of thru moving traffic
minimizing a potential slowing vehicle obstacle. This scenario also provides better roadway efficiency.
Cons: Grade challenges, most likely requiring a retaining wall, present issues that could drive up cost.
The north side path would be offset from a straight alignment and/or need to be reduced.
6. Full complement of east/westbound turn lanes at Hardwood Avenue: Hardwood Avenue has been
the location of the most severe crashes in the project area. The location at the bottom of a sag curve
has added to challenges for thru traffic flow interacting with stopping or slowing vehicles at the
intersection. Pros: Installing a full complement of turn lanes at Harwood Avenue would move turning
vehicles out of the way of thru traffic thus alleviating some of the grade/slope conflict areas. Previous
improvements to the intersection undertaken by Washington County in 2008 placed the southwest
signal pole in a location that would allow for a south-shifted roadway. Cons: Large grade challenges to
the northeast of the intersection would most likely require roadway shifting to the south. Retaining
walls would be needed to ensure that the roadway grade tie-in points remain within Washington County

text.b: 7. Temporary traffic signal with additional turn lane construction at the intersection of CSAH 22 and

page.text: Hinton Avenue: Traffic volumes are expected to meet traffic signal warrants by 2030. A temporary
signal can be implemented at the intersection with additional turn lanes to meet Washington County
standards to mitigate expected traffic operation difficulties with the current all-way stop control. Pros:
A traffic signal will provide improved traffic operations at the intersection. Temporary signal can be an
effective traffic control device for an indefinite amount of time. Cons: All traffic signals require
continual maintenance which would increase overall cost. The construction of additional turns lanes at
the intersection would be needed to meet Washington County signalized intersection layout standards.
Interim Improvements are categorized into overall project cost and complexity. Improvements
considered more complex involve full roadway shifts and retaining wall construction. Cost calculations
do not incorporate potential storm sewer adjustments associated with each option. Estimated Interim
improvement costs are shown in Table 9. Unit cost breakdowns can be found in Appendix F.

text.b: Signalized Intersection - CSAH 22 at Meadow Grass Avenue

page.text: Initial analysis of traffic operations based on projected 2030 traffic volumes at the intersection of CSAH
22 and Meadow Grass Avenue indicated that the intersection will be close to meeting traffic signal
warrants. If traffic volumes increase to the point that warrants are met, consideration should be given
to expanding the intersection to provide a full complement of turn lanes at all approaches.
Incorporating additional turn lanes will help provide additional future capacity. This may be needed if
Meadow Grass Avenue is ever extended to the north and south to serve a larger traffic generating area.
Intersection operations analysis should be undertaken in the future to analyze if traffic signal warrants
are expected to be met. Figure 6 details an expanded layout that can be incorporated with a traffic

text.b: Roadway Connectivity - Goodview and Granada to Meadow Grass Avenue

page.text: The installation of 3/4 accesses at the intersections of CSAH 22 and Goodview and Granada Avenues
would require some impacted residents to take a more circuitous route in order to make left turns onto
CSAH 22 from their respective neighborhoods. Providing alternative connection routes from each of
these roadways to Meadow Grass Avenue to reach the proposed full access would provide for more
uniform traffic movements at Meadow Grass Avenue and fewer u-turn movements. U-turns are a safe
and legal movement, however, they are not always popular.
An alternative intersection operation improvement at CSAH 22 and Hinton Avenue is a roundabout. The
balanced traffic volumes provide for an ideal location for the implementation of a roundabout.
Roundabouts can improve safety and may provide traffic operations comparable to or better than that
of a traffic signal depending the situation. Figure 6 provides a detailed layout of how a roundabout
could be incorporated into the proposed intersection of CSAH 22 and Hinton Avenue. Another benefit
of a roundabout at the intersection is that the eastern most project limits can be reduced because the
eastbound lane drop can be incorporated into the roundabout itself. *Note: The roundabout layout

text.i: contained in Figure 7 is consider preliminary. The intention of this layout is to tie into the existing
roadway and show eastern corridor project limits. Exact roundabout configuration will need to be
identified at a later date if selected for final design.

page.text: A high-level engineering visual review of traffic operations at Hinton Avenue and 69th Street noted that
during peak hours, access delays from 69th Street to Hinton Avenue are quite long. These delays are
expected to grow to unacceptable levels in 2030. Delays are mostly due to the traffic operation
interaction between the all-way stop conditions at CSAH 22 and Hinton Avenue to the south and CSAH
22 at 65th Street to the north. All-way stop conditions allow vehicles to traverse intersections at very
regular intervals. As traffic volumes grow, approaching traffic may stack as the rate of arrival may
surpass the rate of departure thru the intersection. The stacking and consistent arrival of vehicles may
